        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is brown noise?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>Brown noise (or red noise) is an acoustic signal with a spectral density that is inversely proportional to the square of the frequency (1/fÂ²). This means its energy decreases by 6 dB per octave as the frequency increases, producing a deep, bass-heavy rumble that sounds like heavy rain, distant thunder, or a waterfall.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is brown noise harmful?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>No, brown noise is not harmful when listened to at safe volume levels (ideally below 70-85 decibels for adults, and below 50 decibels for babies). In fact, it is a non-pharmacological sleep and focus aid. To protect your hearing, keep volumes moderate and avoid direct, close proximity to speakers or headphones.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is brown noise good for?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>Brown noise is exceptionally good for auditory masking, helping block disruptive background sounds like traffic or chatter. It is widely used to improve sleep quality, promote deep focus and concentration (especially for studying or work), soothe babies, reduce symptoms of tinnitus, and manage ADHD.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is brown noise good for sleep?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>Yes, brown noise is highly effective for sleep. Its deep, warm frequency profile helps mask sudden, disruptive night noises. This steady auditory blanket prevents your brain from waking up due to environmental changes, facilitating a deeper and more continuous sleep.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What does brown noise do?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>Brown noise works by raising the acoustic baseline in your environment. By filling the background with a steady, low-frequency hum, it masks sudden sounds that would otherwise distract you or wake you up. This helps calm the nervous system, lower stress, and enhance focus.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is brown noise vs white noise?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>While white noise contains all audible frequencies in equal measure, resulting in a bright, static-like hiss, brown noise emphasizes lower frequencies. Brown noise drops off by 6 dB per octave at higher frequencies, making it sound much deeper, warmer, and less harsh than white noise.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What does brown noise sound like?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>Brown noise sounds like a deep, heavy, and steady rumble. Common comparisons include a heavy, distant rainstorm, a large waterfall, ocean surf, or the low hum of a jet passenger cabin. It lacks the sharp, high-pitched hiss found in white noise.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Does brown noise help you sleep?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>Yes, brown noise helps you sleep by reducing the dynamic range of sounds in your room. When sudden noises occur, they do not stand out against the background hum, preventing your auditory cortex from reacting and interrupting your sleep cycle.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Does brown noise make you poop?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>No, the concept of a frequency that causes bowel movements (often called the \"brown note\") is a popular urban myth. Scientific testing has shown that the \"brown note\" is not real, and listening to normal brown noise has no laxative effect.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between white noise and brown noise?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>The main difference lies in the frequency spectrum balance. White noise has equal energy across all frequencies (flat spectrum), sounding like high static. Brown noise has a spectrum where power drops off at higher frequencies (deep bass focus), making it sound much deeper, warmer, and more relaxing.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is brown noise good for babies?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>Yes, brown noise can be very soothing for babies because its low frequencies resemble the loud, swooshing sounds of blood flow heard inside the womb. However, always place the sound source at least 6-7 feet away from the crib, keep the volume under 50 dB, and limit continuous use to sleep times.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is the brown noise real?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>Yes, brown noise is a real, scientifically defined type of sound (often called Brownian noise or red noise). Its name comes from Robert Brown, the discoverer of Brownian motion (random walk), which describes the mathematical process used to generate its signal. It is not named after the color.</p>"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  </script>

